"Your ambient body temperature has dropped zero point four degrees since sunset," GEAR observed from the cart rail. "Is this a concern, or do you simply accept gradual thermal death as a feature of organic existence?"
The Gates
They crested the last hill before the Rift valley opened below them.
And there it was. Riften. Sitting on the shore of Lake Honrich exactly where they'd left it. The autumn canopy framing the city walls in gold and amber and red. Smoke rising from chimneys ΓÇö chimneys, not pyres. The lake shimmering in the afternoon light.
No black flags. No barricades. No locked gates. No army of the desperate and dying pressed against the walls begging for entry.
The road ahead was clear. A merchant cart was rolling toward the city from the south. Two fishermen were walking home with their catch. A child was throwing stones into the lake.
The city they had traveled for days to save did not need saving. It barely looked like it noticed anything had happened.
They rode down the hill in silence. GEAR's eye swiveled constantly ΓÇö cataloguing organic architecture for the first time, studying the walls, the gates, the people moving through the streets with the fascinated attention of a machine that had never seen a child or a merchant or a building made of wood.
A guard at the gate glanced at the cart ΓÇö at the battered, exhausted group slumped against the rails, the weapons strapped to the sides, the brass sphere perched on the railing, the empty seat where a Khajiit used to sit ΓÇö and waved them through.
"Welcome back to Riften."
A pause.
"Good timing, too. Your priestess handled the plague business. Black-Briar's paying for the cleanup. You lot are popular around here."
Your priestess. He knew they were Lanterns. He was crediting their company. For something they had nothing to do with.
Posted at the gate, on official parchment bearing Maven Black-Briar's seal:
The people of the Rift owe their lives to the courage and devotion of the OBSIDIAN LANTERNS and their priestess DANICA PURE-SPRING. Through her tireless efforts and personal sacrifice, the contagion that threatened our city has been eradicated and our beloved Hemming Black-Briar restored to health. The Black-Briar family extends its eternal gratitude.
Their name. Their company. On the wall. For the greatest heroic act the Obsidian Lanterns had ever performed.
And none of them had been in the room when it happened.
Davinia read the notice twice. Danica's name in official script, credited to the Lanterns, sealed by Maven Black-Briar. The woman she'd pushed away ΓÇö the priestess she'd smacked away at Korvanjund, the healer she'd driven into the wilderness ΓÇö had saved a city, cured a plague, and rescued Maven's heir.
Without them. Because of them. Because Davinia had pushed her away, and Danica had gone where she was needed instead of where she was wanted.
The notice was the kindest thing and the cruelest thing on the wall.
They passed through the gates of Riften. The autumn air was warm. The leaves were golden. The lake was still.
Behind them, the road they'd traveled stretched north ΓÇö through the Rift's dying roots, past a scorched mountain pass where a dragon's bones were cooling, through the frozen Pale where a brass ruin sat sealed and humming, all the way to a glacier that sang in a frequency only the dead could hear.
Ahead, a city that didn't need them. A priestess who had saved it without them. And the knowledge, heavy as the Crown on Davinia's head, that the only truly heroic thing the Obsidian Lanterns had ever done happened entirely because they were somewhere else.

